{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636499"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:29:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:29:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17581"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17581"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.11,0.04,0.07,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10271"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71372"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10271"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56848"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10076"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24004"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71372"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETriglycerides serve as the body\u0027s main form of energy storage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary storage site of triglycerides in the human body?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancreatic cells within zymogen granules","Liver cells within vesicles","Muscle cells within mitochondria","Blood plasma within lipoproteins","Adipose tissue within adipocytes"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdipose tissue within adipocytes\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary storage site for triglycerides in the human body. These specialised cells contain a single large lipid droplet that can occupy up to 90% of the cell volume. The triglycerides are stored in an anhydrous form, making this an extremely efficient means of energy storage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver cells within vesicles\u003C/strong\u003E - While the liver can store some triglycerides, this is not the primary storage site and excessive hepatic triglyceride storage is pathological\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle cells within mitochondria\u003C/strong\u003E - Mitochondria are sites of fatty acid oxidation, not storage. Muscle cells store minimal amounts of triglycerides\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic cells within zymogen granules\u003C/strong\u003E - Zymogen granules contain digestive enzyme precursors, not stored lipids\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood plasma within lipoproteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Lipoproteins transport lipids but are not a significant storage form\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe storage and mobilisation of triglycerides in adipose tissue is tightly regulated by hormones, particularly insulin which promotes storage and glucagon which promotes breakdown.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Triglycerides are stored primarily in adipose tissue within specialised cells called adipocytes.","Adipocytes contain a single large lipid droplet that occupies most of the cell volume.","Triglyceride storage and breakdown is regulated by hormones including insulin and glucagon."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Editi